{{For|other people with similar names|Gyula Katona (disambiguation)}}
'''Gyula Y. Katona''' (born December 4, 1965) is a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[mathematician]], the son of mathematician [[Gyula O. H. Katona]]. He received his Ph.D. in 1997 from [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]], with a dissertation entitled ''Paths and Cycles in Graphs and Hypergraphs'' under the advisement of [[László Lovász]] and [[András Recski]], and {{As of|2009|lc=on}} is on the faculty of the [[Budapest University of Technology and Economics]].

Katona is the coauthor of three textbooks, ''Introduction to Computer Science'' (Typotex, Budapest, 2002), ''Introduction to Finite Mathematics'', (Eötvös L. University, Budapest, 1993), and ''Combinatorics, Graph Theory and Algorithms'' (Technical University of Budapest, 1993). In addition his research publications include several works on [[Hamiltonian cycle]]s and related properties of graphs.

